<p> the capacity to systematically visit detention centres in Nepal; it has also been 
slow to conduct and conclude investigations and for those cases where it has made 
recommendations, the Government has time and again failed to implement them.  
</p>
<p>A new bill setting out the powers of the NHRC as a constitutional body only 
provides the NHRC with access to prisons. It is essential in the light of the 
ongoing use of torture in police custody as well as the documented practice of 
using unofficial places of detention such as army camps and private houses (see 
above) to detain people that the bill provides the NHRC with access to &#8220;any place 
where people are held captive&#8221;. It is also necessary for the wording of this section 
to make it clear that this also covers any &#8220;detention facilities&#8221; run by non-State 
actors.  
